Section section_01 (Chars 0–8551):
Section Summary: In 1820, the remains of a great city in Ancient Egypt were discovered in Middle Egypt, and in 1888, a number of clay tablets were found near the ruins of Tell el Amarna. The tablets, written in Babylonian cuneiform, were part of the Egyptian state archives during the reigns of Kings Amenophis III and IV, and consisted mainly of letters from Egyptian officials and Asiatic kings to the Egyptian monarch. The discovery revealed that Babylonian was the language of diplomacy in the East around 1400 B.C. The tablets provided valuable insights into the administration and court of Ancient Egypt, including the reigns of Kings Thutmosis III, Amenophis II, and Amenophis III, who shifted the focus from war to more cultural and religious pursuits. The tablets also shed light on the attempts of King Amenophis IV to reform the Egyptian religion, introducing a form of monotheism that worshipped the sun disk.
